    "body_text": [
        {
            "endOffset": 88266,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0370": {
                    "endOffset": 88042,
                    "startOffset": 88012
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "Takei and Hier-Majumder (2009) proposed that compaction coincident with dissolution and precipitation provides mode selection governed by a chemical diffusion length scale, which is indeed similar to the widest band spacing, although not the band widths.",
            "startOffset": 88012,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 86560,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0220": {
                    "endOffset": 86558,
                    "startOffset": 86530
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "Such melt banding may provide high-permeability pathways that strongly influence the transport of melt to the Earth's surface (Kohlstedt and Holtzman, 2009).",
            "startOffset": 86403,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 95882,
            "parents": [
                {
                    "id": "se0020",
                    "title": "Theory"
                },
                {
                    "id": "se0050",
                    "title": "Dynamics"
                }
            ],
            "secId": "se0060",
            "sentence": "The interface drag coefficient is denoted by c and is typically proportional to the ratio of melt viscosity to matrix permeability; however, for the sake of simplicity there is no need to introduce a new variable yet, and we merely need to note that c is also a function of \u03d5.",
            "startOffset": 95606,
            "title": "Constitutive laws and rheology"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 89383,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "Below we briefly develop the concept of the diffuse interface coincident with microscopic interfaces, and demonstrate how it can predict mode selection at the observed melt-band wavelengths.",
            "startOffset": 89193,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 88989,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "However, capillary effects at the microscopic (i.e., pore/grain) scale cannot give the necessary effect (as will be demonstrated herein).",
            "startOffset": 88852,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 86402,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0110": {
                    "endOffset": 86319,
                    "startOffset": 86234
                },
                "br0150": {
                    "endOffset": 86319,
                    "startOffset": 86234
                },
                "br0210": {
                    "endOffset": 86319,
                    "startOffset": 86234
                },
                "br0280": {
                    "endOffset": 86319,
                    "startOffset": 86234
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "In particular, sheared partial melts have been demonstrated in laboratory experiments (Daines and Kohlstedt, 1997; Holtzman et al., 2003; King et al., 2010; Qi et al., 2013) to develop narrow melt bands at shallow angles (\u223c20\u00b0) to the direction of motion.",
            "startOffset": 86147,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 87717,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0020": {
                    "endOffset": 87715,
                    "startOffset": 87663
                },
                "br0080": {
                    "endOffset": 87715,
                    "startOffset": 87663
                },
                "br0180": {
                    "endOffset": 87715,
                    "startOffset": 87663
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "The failure to predict mode selection has been a significant conundrum for understanding the physics let alone believing the theories, and is problematic for numerical simulations for which instabilities shrink to the grid-scale, and thus cannot be resolved (Katz et al., 2006; Butler, 2012; Alisic et al., 2014).",
            "startOffset": 87404,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 108732,
            "parents": [
                {
                    "id": "se0110",
                    "title": "Discussion and conclusion: application to melt band experiments"
                }
            ],
            "secId": "se0130",
            "sentence": "That the spacing is wider than the band width possibly reflects a nonlinear effect whereby the melt-rich bands drain melt from the surrounding matrix, but only as far away as some larger fraction of the compaction length; however, this assumption needs testing with nonlinear models with our proposed mechanism.",
            "startOffset": 108421,
            "title": "Mode selection and comparison to experiments"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 86146,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0120": {
                    "endOffset": 86144,
                    "startOffset": 86065
                },
                "br0130": {
                    "endOffset": 86144,
                    "startOffset": 86065
                },
                "br0170": {
                    "endOffset": 86144,
                    "startOffset": 86065
                },
                "br0330": {
                    "endOffset": 86144,
                    "startOffset": 86065
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "Indeed, the unique deformation of partial melts likely controls flow and strain focussing at both convergent and divergent plate boundaries (e.g., Spiegelman and McKenzie, 1987; Katz, 2008; Gerya and Meilick, 2011; Gerya, 2013).",
            "startOffset": 85918,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 85917,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0100": {
                    "endOffset": 85915,
                    "startOffset": 85899
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "While mantle melting only occurs within a small volume of the Earth, it plays a disproportionate role in both geochemical evolution and plate-boundary processes (see Cox et al., 1993).",
            "startOffset": 85733,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 87403,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0150": {
                    "endOffset": 87356,
                    "startOffset": 87275
                },
                "br0160": {
                    "endOffset": 87356,
                    "startOffset": 87275
                },
                "br0220": {
                    "endOffset": 87356,
                    "startOffset": 87275
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "Laboratory experiments, however, show that while the melt bands are very narrow, of order a few to tens of microns wide, and with band spacing roughly an order of magnitude wider (Holtzman et al., 2003; Holtzman and Kohlstedt, 2007; Kohlstedt and Holtzman, 2009), they are consistently not vanishingly small.",
            "startOffset": 87095,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 87094,
            "parents": [],
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "An equally significant enigma is that current two-phase models cannot predict the basic melt band width, since they infer the fastest growing instability to have zero wavelength.",
            "startOffset": 86916,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 88573,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0010": {
                    "endOffset": 88395,
                    "startOffset": 88374
                },
                "br0150": {
                    "endOffset": 88571,
                    "startOffset": 88550
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "However, while such chemical reactions between phases are expected to be important in geological settings (Aharonov et al., 1997), their role was not evident in the laboratory experiments, which were designed to study melt channels by stress alone and avoid reaction channelization (Holtzman et al., 2003).",
            "startOffset": 88267,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 89192,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0360": {
                    "endOffset": 89190,
                    "startOffset": 89166
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "In this paper, we propose a small adjustment to existing theories that involves a diffuse interface effect, which occurs at very large gradients in melt volume fraction (e.g., Sun and Beckermann, 2004).",
            "startOffset": 88990,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 86915,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0080": {
                    "endOffset": 86913,
                    "startOffset": 86750
                },
                "br0180": {
                    "endOffset": 86913,
                    "startOffset": 86750
                },
                "br0190": {
                    "endOffset": 86913,
                    "startOffset": 86750
                },
                "br0310": {
                    "endOffset": 86913,
                    "startOffset": 86750
                },
                "br0320": {
                    "endOffset": 86913,
                    "startOffset": 86750
                },
                "br0350": {
                    "endOffset": 86913,
                    "startOffset": 86750
                },
                "br0380": {
                    "endOffset": 86913,
                    "startOffset": 86750
                },
                "br0390": {
                    "endOffset": 86913,
                    "startOffset": 86750
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "The observed shallow angle of these melt bands is enigmatic and has been the subject of several theoretical studies invoking two-phase compaction theory with various rheological mechanisms (Stevenson, 1989; Spiegelman, 2003; Katz et al., 2006; Takei and Holtzman, 2009; Butler, 2012; Takei and Katz, 2013; Katz and Takei, 2013; Rudge and Bercovici, 2015).",
            "startOffset": 86560,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 88011,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0070": {
                    "endOffset": 87731,
                    "startOffset": 87718
                },
                "br0320": {
                    "endOffset": 87916,
                    "startOffset": 87899
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "Butler (2010) proposed that, in the finite strain limit, the rotation of bands through the optimal angle of growth can amplify larger wavelength bands, although as shown earlier by Spiegelman (2003) this effect depends on the initial conditions for the structure of the porosity perturbations.",
            "startOffset": 87718,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 88851,
            "parents": [],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0040": {
                    "endOffset": 88807,
                    "startOffset": 88712
                },
                "br0060": {
                    "endOffset": 88807,
                    "startOffset": 88712
                },
                "br0140": {
                    "endOffset": 88807,
                    "startOffset": 88712
                },
                "br0340": {
                    "endOffset": 88807,
                    "startOffset": 88712
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0010",
            "sentence": "Here we consider two-phase compaction theory that includes capillary effects from the interface between phases, i.e., the melt and matrix (Stevenson, 1986; Bercovici et al., 2001; Bercovici and Ricard, 2003; Hier-Majumder et al., 2006), as a means for explaining mode selection.",
            "startOffset": 88573,
            "title": "Introduction"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 108420,
            "parents": [
                {
                    "id": "se0110",
                    "title": "Discussion and conclusion: application to melt band experiments"
                }
            ],
            "secId": "se0130",
            "sentence": "The difference between the melt band widths and their spacing in each case indicates two dominant length scales of the instability; this cannot be explained by our linear stability theory, which only predicts one least-stable mode.",
            "startOffset": 108189,
            "title": "Mode selection and comparison to experiments"
        },
        {
            "endOffset": 108930,
            "parents": [
                {
                    "id": "se0110",
                    "title": "Discussion and conclusion: application to melt band experiments"
                }
            ],
            "refoffsets": {
                "br0070": {
                    "endOffset": 108928,
                    "startOffset": 108916
                },
                "br0370": {
                    "endOffset": 108864,
                    "startOffset": 108834
                }
            },
            "secId": "se0130",
            "sentence": "Alternatively, the wide spacing could reflect the chemical-diffusion limited instability proposed by Takei and Hier-Majumder (2009) or the effect of finite strain and rotation (e.g., Butler, 2010).",
            "startOffset": 108733,
            "title": "Mode selection and comparison to experiments"
        }
